          + Interesting Reads

Books

     * [http://www-nlp.stanford.edu/IR-book/]Introduction to Information
       Retrieval - C.D. Manning, P. Raghavan, H. Schütze. Cambridge UP,
       2008. (First book for getting started with Information Retrieval).
     * [http://ciir.cs.umass.edu/downloads/SEIRiP.pdf]Search Engines:
       Information Retrieval in Practice - Bruce Croft, Don Metzler, and
       Trevor Strohman. 2009. (Great book for readers interested in
       knowing how Search Engines work. The book is very detailed).
     * [http://people.ischool.berkeley.edu/%7Ehearst/irbook/]Modern
       Information Retrieval - R. Baeza-Yates, B. Ribeiro-Neto.
       Addison-Wesley, 1999.
     * [http://www.search-engines-book.com/]Information Retrieval in
       Practice - B. Croft, D. Metzler, T. Strohman. Pearson Education,
       2009.
     * [http://www.cse.iitb.ac.in/%7Esoumen/mining-the-web/]Mining the
       Web: Analysis of Hypertext and Semi Structured Data - S.
       Chakrabarti. Morgan Kaufmann, 2002.
     * [http://www.springer.com/prod/b/1-4020-1216-0?referer=www.wkap.nl]L
       anguage Modeling for Information Retrieval - W.B. Croft, J.
       Lafferty. Springer, 2003. (Handles Language Modeling aspect of
       Information Retrieval. It also extensively details probabilistic
       perspective in this domain, which is interesting).
     * [http://www.csee.umbc.edu/cadip/readings/IR.report.120600.book.pdf]
       Information Retrieval: A Survey - Ed Greengrass, 2000.
       (Comprehensive survey of Conventional Information Retrieval, before
       Deep Learning era).
     * [https://www.amazon.com/Introduction-Modern-Information-Retrieval-T
       hird/dp/185604694X]Introduction to Modern Information Retrieval -
       G.G. Chowdhury. Neal-Schuman, 2003. (Intended for students of
       library and information studies).
     * [https://www.amazon.com/Information-Retrieval-Systems-Library-Hardc
       over/dp/0123694124]Text Information Retrieval Systems - C.T.
       Meadow, B.R. Boyce, D.H. Kraft, C.L. Barry. Academic Press, 2007
       (library/information science perspective).

Courses

     * [http://courses.ischool.utexas.edu/Lease_Matt/2016/Fall/INF384H/]IN
       F384H / CS395T / INF350E: Concepts of Information Retrieval (and
       Web Search) - Matthew Lease (University of Texas at Austin).
     * [http://web.stanford.edu/class/cs276/]CS 276 / LING 286:
       Information Retrieval and Web Search - Chris Manning and Pandu
       Nayak (Stanford University).
     * [https://www.cs.utexas.edu/%7Emooney/ir-course/]CS 371R:
       Information Retrieval and Web Search - Raymond J. Mooney
       (University of Texas at Austin).
     * [http://www.cs.ucr.edu/%7Evagelis/classes/CS172/]CS 172:
       Introduction to Information Retrieval - Vagelis Hristidis
       (University of California - Riverside).
     * [http://www2.sims.berkeley.edu/academics/courses/is240/s06/]SIMS
       240: Principles of Information Retrieval - Ray R. Larson (UC
       berkeley).
     * [http://boston.lti.cs.cmu.edu/classes/11-642/]11-442 / 11-642:
       Search Engines - Jamie Callan (CMU).
     * [http://www.cs.jhu.edu/%7Eyarowsky/cs466.html]600.466: Information
       Retrieval and Web Agents - David Yarowsky (John Hopkins
       University).
     * [http://www.cs.princeton.edu/courses/archive/spring06/cos435/]CS
       435: Information Retrieval, Discovery, and Delivery - Andrea
       LaPaugh (Princeton University).
     * [https://www.mpi-inf.mpg.de/departments/databases-and-information-s
       ystems/teaching/winter-semester-201516/information-retrieval-and-da
       ta-mining/]Information Retrieval and Data Mining - Dr. Jilles
       Vreeken , Prof. Dr. Gerhard Weikum (MPI).
     * [http://www.cse.unsw.edu.au/%7Ecs6714/17s2/index.html]COMP6714
       Information Retrieval and Web Search - Prof. Wei Wang (University
       of New South Wales).
     * [https://www.coursera.org/learn/text-retrieval]Coursera - Text
       Retrieval and Search Engines - Prof. ChengXiang Zhai (University of
       Illinois at Urbana-Champaign).

Software

     * [http://lucene.apache.org/core/]Apache Lucene - Open Source Search
       Engine that can be used to test Information Retrieval Algorithm.
       Twitter uses this core for its real-time search.
     * [http://www.lemurproject.org/]The Lemur Project - The Lemur Project
       develops search engines, browser toolbars, text analysis tools, and
       data resources that support research and development of information
       retrieval and text mining software.
          + [http://www.lemurproject.org/indri.php]Indri Search Engine -
            Another Open Source Search Engine competitor of Apache Lucene.
          + [http://www.lemurproject.org/lemur.php]Lemur Toolkit - Open
            Source Toolkit for research in Language Modeling, filtering
            and categorization.

Datasets

Standard IR Collections

     * [http://wiki.dbpedia.org/Downloads2015-10]DBPedia - Linked data
       web.
     * [http://ir.dcs.gla.ac.uk/resources/test_collections/cran/]Cranfield
       Collections - This is one of the first collections in IR domain,
       however the dataset is too small for any statistical significance
       analysis, but is nevertheless suitable for pilot runs.
     * [http://trec.nist.gov/data.html]TREC Collections - TREC is the
       benchmark dataset used by most IR and Web search algorithms. It has
       several tracks, each of which consists of dataset to test for a
       specific task. The tracks along with suggested use-case are:
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/blog.html]Blog - Explore
            information seeking behavior in the blogosphere.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/chem-ir.html]Chemical IR - Address
            challenges in building large chemical testbeds for chemical
            IR.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/clinical.html]Clinical Decision
            Support - Investigate techniques to link medical cases to
            information relevant for patient care.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/confusion.html]Confusion - Study
            [http://trec.nist.gov/data/confusion/t5confusion.ps]Known Item
            Searching problem.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/context.html]Contextual Suggestion
            - Investigate search techniques for complex information needs
            (context and user interests based).
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/crowd.html]Crowdsourcing - Explore
            crowdsourcing methods for performing and evaluating search.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/enterprise.html]Enterprise - Study
            search over the organization data.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/entity.html]Entity - Perform
            entity-related search (find entities and their properties) on
            Web data.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/filtering.html]Filtering - Binarily
            decide retrieval of new incoming documents given a stable
            information need.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/federated.html]Federated Web Search
            - Study merge performance for results from various search
            services.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/genomics.html]Genomics - Study
            retrieval efficiency of genomics data and corresponding
            documentation.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/hard.html]HARD - Obtain High
            Accuracy Retrieval from Documents by leveraging searcher's
            context.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/interactive.html]Interactive Track
            - Study user interaction with text retrieval systems.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/kba.html]Knowledge base
            acceleration - Study algorithms that improve efficiency of
            human Knowledge Base.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/legal.html]Legal Track - Study
            retrieval systems that have high recall for legal documents
            use case.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/medical.html]Medical Track -
            Explore unstructured search performance over patients record
            data.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/microblog.html]Microblog Track -
            Examine satisfaction of real-time information need for
            microblogging sites.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/million.query.html]Million Query
            Track - Explore ad-hoc retrieval over large set of queries.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/novelty.html]Novelty Track -
            Investigate systems' abilities to locate new (non-redundant)
            information.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/qamain.html]Question Answering
            Track - Test systems that scale beyond document retrieval, to
            retrieve answers to factoid, list and definition type
            questions.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/relevance.feedback.html]Relevance
            Feedback Track - For deep evaluation of relevance feedback
            processes.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/robust.html]Robust Track - Study
            individual topic's effectiveness.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/session.html]Session Track -
            Develop methods for measuring multiple-query sessions where
            information needs drift.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/spam.html]SPAM Track - Benchmark
            spam filtering approaches.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/tasks.html]Tasks Track - Test if
            systems can induce possible tasks, users might be trying to
            accomplish for the query.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/tempsumm.html]Temporal
            Summarization Track - Develop systems that allow users to
            efficiently monitor the information associated with an event
            over time.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/terabyte.html]Terabyte Track - Test
            scalability of IR systems to large scale collection.
          + [http://trec.nist.gov/data/webmain.html]Web Track - Explore
            information seeking behaviors common in general web search.
     * [http://ir.dcs.gla.ac.uk/test_collections/gov2-summary.htm]GOV2
       Test Collection - This is one of the largest Web collection of
       documents obtained from crawl of government websites by Charlie
       Clarke and Ian Soboroff, using NIST hardware and network, then
       formatted by Nick Craswel.
     * [http://research.nii.ac.jp/ntcir/data/data-en.html]NTCIR Test
       Collection - This is collection of wide variety of dataset ranging
       from Ad-hoc collection, Chinese IR collection, mobile clickthrough
       collections to medical collections. The focus of this collection is
       mostly on east asian languages and cross language information
       retrieval.
          + [http://research.nii.ac.jp/ntcir/permission/ntcir-6/perm-en-CL
            IR.html]CLIR Test Collections - This dataset can be used for
            cross lingual IR between CJKE
            (Chinese-Japanese-Korean-English) languages. It is suitable
            for the following tasks:
               o Multilingual CLIR
               o Bilingual CLIR
               o Single Language CLIR
          + [http://research.nii.ac.jp/ntcir/permission/ntcir-6/perm-en-CL
            QA.html]Cross Language Q&A (CLQA) dataset collection - It
            supports following bi-lingua and mono-lingua:
               o Bi-lingua
                    # Japanese to English.
                    # Chinese to English.
                    # English to Japanese.
                    # English to Chinese.
               o Mono-lingua
                    # Chinese to Chinese.
                    # Japanese to Japanese.
                    # English to English.
          + [http://research.nii.ac.jp/ntcir/permission/ntcir-8/perm-en-AC
            LIA.html]Advanced Cross Linugal Information Retrieval and
            Question Answering (ACLIA) - The dataset is used for the task
            of cross-lingual question answering but the complexity of the
            task is higher than CLQA dataset.
     * [http://www.clef-initiative.eu/dataset/test-collection]Conference
       and Labs of the Evaluation Forum (CLEF) dataset - It contains a
       multi-lingual document collection. The test suite includes:
          + AdHoc - News Test suite.
          + Domain Specific Test Suite - On collections of scientific
            articles.
          + Question Answering Test Suite.
     * [http://trec.nist.gov/data/reuters/reuters.html]Reuters Corpora -
       The corpora is now available through NIST. The corpora includes
       following:
          + RCV1 (Reuter's Corpus Volume 1) - Consists of only English
            language News stories.
          + RCV2 (Reuter's Corpus Volume 2) - Consists of stories in 13
            languages (Dutch, French, German, Chinese, Japanese, Russian,
            Portuguese, Spanish, Latin American Spanish, Italian, Danish,
            Norwegian, and Swedish). Note that the stories are not
            parallel.
          + TRC (Thomson Reuters Text Research Collection) - This is a
            fairly recent corpus consisting of 1,800,370 news stories
            covering the period from 2008-01-01 00:00:03 to 2009-02-28
            23:54:14.
     * [https://kdd.ics.uci.edu/databases/20newsgroups/20newsgroups.html]2
       0 Newsgroup dataset - This data set consists of 20000 newsgroup
       messages.posts taken from 20 newsgroup topics.
     * [https://catalog.ldc.upenn.edu/LDC2011T07]English Gigaword Fifth
       Edition - This data set is a comprehensive archive of English
       newswire text data including headlines, datelines and articles.
     * [http://www-nlpir.nist.gov/projects/duc/data.html]Document
       Understanding Conference (DUC) datasets - Past newswire/paper
       datasets (DUC 2001 - DUC 2007) are available upon request.

